Labour and delivery may be induced by intravenous (IV) Pitocin, which stimulates uterine contraction. Pitocin is the trade name of a hormone released from what endocrine tissue?
That's right!  Oxytocin, produced by the posterior pituitary, stimulates uterine contraction.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The hypothalamic-hypophyseal tract occupies the infundibulum of the posterior pituitary. It consists of axons arising from neurons in two hypothalamic nuclei, which pass through the infundibulum into the posterior pituitary. These are the supraoptic and the paraventricular nuclei, the neurons of which produce antidiuretic hormone (ADH) and oxytocin, respectively. 
The hormones are transported to axon terminals in the posterior pituitary, where they are stored until their release into the surrounding interstitial fluid. From there, the hormones are picked up by capillaries formed from the inferior hypophyseal artery, which drain into the venous blood of the cavernous sinuses and ultimately the internal jugular vein.

Antidiuretic hormone, ADH is also known as vasopressin. It acts on the kidney to promote retention of water, thus increasing blood volume and pressure.
Oxytocin causes contraction of myoepithelial cells of the mammary glands, and thus promotes the ejection of milk. During childbirth, oxytocin stimulates the contraction of uterine smooth muscle.
